annotation: Decided to try the Moscow variation against the Semi-Slav defense.
I believe this denies me the Marcozy bind.
prevents Nb5 from targeting his d pawn. I wasn't really looking at that though was eyeing the nice d5 perch for my knight.
And so I try to drive that knight of his away.
took the exchange because it allows me that perch.
A good position for his bishop to be ... for a long time this bishop would prove to be a key factor keeping my knight at d5.
I think this was to attempt b4 to dislodge his annoying c pawn.
b3 instead of b4 because I did not wish to break my pawn structure in the center and because if the exchange took place my rook was in a better position to control the b file.
I castled as well as a "wait and see" option.
I think my intention was to push f4 to force the e pawn off and control the f file using my rook.

This was what I was afraid of when I moved my knight from f3. While my queen currently prevents that knight (in the same way his bishop is placed) from causing any trouble I do not want the queen to be inactive because of that.
Sticking to the plan.
Aiming to remove that possibly dangerous knight from play.
While it was true I threatened the e pawn that was not really my main goal.
probably superior to exd4 as it does not expose his king-side to a possible pass-pawn.
I had to remove the danger of bxc4 as that gives him sufficient tempo to bring his rook to control the c file.

that seals up the queen-side for a while. a5 simply buys me a tempo for it is far to my advantage for me to move axb4 than bxa5. Now my attention (and worries) have to be directed at the f file. f5 followed by fxe4 would sink my knight.

My only reasonable defense I believe. 21. ... fxe4  22. Qxe4 exposes his weaker rook to my stronger doubled rook. At the same time my knight is kept alive by the queen but just barely. I believe my plan was to do Nb6 for the bishop-knight exchange if it looked like he could pressure my queen. 22. Qxe4 Rf4 would force a rook exchange that probably gives me a stronger positional advantage.
This was troubling. 22. ... Rf5 could mean penetration of my defenses.

Not sure why I did this ... I think it was to attack the pawn on the e file (helping to secure the f pawn) but it almost got my queen trapped without hope. I believe 22. g4 ... 23. h3 would have served me better.
Notice my queen is almost trapped.
I certainly did not notice that at the time. My obsession was to double the rook on the f file for the attack.
Still oblivious to the danger my queen was in.

This move woke me up. 24 ... g6 loses me the game. My original plan of 24. g3 to force an advantages pawn exchange would have trapped my queen beyond rescue. For now the queen is safe if my g pawn stayed where it was but I had very little room for error and very few options if I kept the g pawn in place.

Which led to this. The plan was to pull the queen to the safety of h3 in response to g6 and then back-off to g2 so I could push h3 to shore up my defenses. This of course leaves me vulnerable to h5 which could lead to an exchange where I have a rather weak pawn on the g file.
moving his king gave me an opportunity for an attack. Qxg5 wins a free bishop if he does nothing about it.
This was starting to get uncomfortably dangerous.
The queen exchange might have been a blunder on his part. Made things somewhat safer for me. The h rook is still in the same danger of g6 though which wins him a tempo since i would have to withdraw.
not sure I understood the intent of this move.

I prefered Kf3 instead of Rf3 because I sensed that if he did Ra8 I could respond with Ra1 in order to support the a pawn in the event of a5 ... axb4 ... Nxb4 (axb4 would be a terrible move on my part).
Back to the annoying position for his bishop.
This is to allow Rhf3 continuing to block the pawn while freeing both my h rook and the h pawn.
He takes advantage of my rush to clear my congested position to pursue an attack on the a file.
I looked at my options and this was the only good one imho. I threaten Rc1 which supports a very dangerous pass-pawn while opening squares for a possible rook attack on his rear pawn structure.
He recognizes the need to prevent my pawn from going further.
At this point I noticed how I can tie 3 of his pieces up using just 2 of my pieces. If I could move my other rook into play that c pawn would be devastating.
Rf1 would take too long. Rf2 followed by Kf3 is the desired shortcut that simultaneously allows my king to physically block his f pawn.
After I made the exchange thinking it was safe I realized a sequence which could have caused me potentially serious problems in my rear - 37. axb4 Ra7 38. Rfc2 Ra3.

Possibly his first blunder. Nxe7 would not be good for me but this move simply gives me the extra time for Rfc2 (which was what I intended in the first place). At the same time the bishop now blocks his f rook from doing anything useful in that constricted position.
Not sure this move buys him much other than freeing the 7th rank for his rook.

The goal is to allow Rc6. In this cramped position dominated by my knight he has few means of preventing the rook from penetrating his defenses. My goal was to get rid of his extremely weak and indefensible b pawn. Of course because his bishop will be forced away from d6 by this move my c pawn remains secure even after I move the rook off the file to attack his b pawn.
His 2nd and most critical blunder i believe. He just walked his king into a position where his bishop would be pinned by my rook (where I wanted to go in the first place).
His only option of holding everything together. Unfortunately it opens his rooks up for a fork by the knight.
I believe this is his final blunder.  41. Nb6 Rcxc7 would have been a far better move. It would still have resulted in pretty much a lost position though.

An English played in the first round of the most recent GK tournament. Black nets an exchange but White manages to cook up some dangerous positions while down in material until the advantage proves too much.

If you're ever going to play me and want to piss me off play the English. Positional play is the hardest for me I much prefer sharp tactical lines which are harder to find in this opening if your opponent doesn't want you to. That being said I believe that I have a winning record against the English...
Aiming for early control of d5 with Bg2
Contesting that control and supporting d7-d5
The battle lines are drawn...or are they?

This move gives 33%/33%/32% in the world for White/Black/Draw. White wanted to play the English but so far I've managed to steer the game in a direction I like open with more tactics at play than positional moves.
A weak square for a knight...
what else?
And here we come out of the database. White tries to gain space and harass the knight but the knight was never planning on staying long at d5 and e4 restricts the bishops scope as well.
?? With the idea of pushing the knight off of e5 and preparing a possible e5 push to lock the White bishop's diagonal down. However a huuge blunder in light of 9.Qh5+ !
An interesting sacrifice the knight was not trapped can White garner an advantage?
Black needs to develop and take control of the center if he's going to survive an assault.
?? Simply a blunder I believe missing the pin on the rook.
? Maybe this deserves a question mark maybe not. Why not capture with the bishop or queen and take control of the diagonal which Black will have a hard time contesting.
Develops the queen takes control of the center gains tempo all around a good move.
Trying to prohibit White's bishop and free Black's.
This move poses no immediate danger to Black but I decide that the outpost is too aggressive.
More tempo lost...
Aiming for a possible trade and clearing house to castle.
I've no qualms in giving White the bishop pair when I'm up a rook and his LSB is severely restricted.
Looking to bring the knight to e6 then possibly g5.
Here begins the danger as White tries to throw the noose around Black's semi-exposed king.
A good move repositioning and activating the Bishop while gaining tempo by pushing the queen around.
Threatening d4 and generally looking to control center squares. I thought about Nd7 first but decided on this instead.
Not wanting to yield e2 or f3.
I spent time here worried that this opened my king too much but after looking for a successful line for White I could not find one and thus took.
A queen trade can only help me now.
Finally this knight joins the party and not a moment too late.
Now the Queen has been given a much less active post and black can use his material advantage to bring home the win.

White's attack seems to have evaporated and now he has a problem to solve his rook is being threatened where to put it? c2 gives black an exchange opportunity and attack both of which White wants to avoid. b1 and a1 are far too passive and allow black to launch an attack indeed every square seems fraught with peril.
White seems to be controlling the open file with his rook but in actuality he is trapping his king...
! The only defense from 38... Rh2# is 38. Rxf3 Qxa5 39. bxa5 exf3 and the game is clearly over.

The Sicilian defense Gloria variation. Seemed fairly common on the gameknot database. I should check out what other sites say about it. My initial instinct was to attempt to attack e4 with Nf6 but it would appear that is premature until we deny e5 with Nc6 followed by d6.

A very complex and potentially problematic position for me. I believe his next intended move is O-O-O which brings his rook against my extremely weak d pawn where any further pressure whether through c5 or Nb5 would cause it to buckle and making further problems for my queen which is currently its only defender and because of the future position of the rook also "safe" because of the rook. I believe my only reasonable move now is Qa5 followed by Rd1. Subsequently I can add defense to the d pawn by Nb4 if necessary (not necessarily wise as it stands now).
Had to defend against an attack on my weak pawn.
To prevent Nb5.

I had to be prepared for 3 scenarios when making the decision to make the knight exchange. 14. Rxd5 looked somewhat problematic but my plan was for Qxa2 and work my way back from there. 14. cxd5 opens up the c file for an eventual attack on the king (after my knight scrams out of the way). 14. exd5 helps clear the way for my e pawn which when pushed opens a diagonal of control for my black bishop to attack his weak b pawn.
I think I wanted more mobility with this move. Nb4 kinda blocks up the queen for no strong reasons.
This is potentially dangerous for me knight is threatened (no support) and I do not wish a scenario where he could place his bishop on h6 and then queen on f6 to hem in the king.
This was kind of a strange move. It gave me ideas that if I could somehow secure h6 I could move the bishop to trap his queen in a pin as long as my own queen was safe.
A somewhat risky move on my part to try for the bishop attack on the queen-king diagonal. I considered 18. g3 Qh5. I kinda wanted him to think I'm going to attack the c pawn (my alternative was Qc7).
I think he saw through both. Unfortunately it does set him up for a much more dangerous scenario though.

Now that the knight is blocking the queen I was going to go for the "cheap" checkmate option of Qxb2 which I expected him to see. Once he took the necessary defenses against that (I was expected Rd2) I was gonna do Bh6 to attack and pin the knight against the queen which forces his queen to f2 allowing me to do Re8 to control the e file and try an attack. 

Unfortunately he did not see the mate threat.
Philidor's Defence
Black's bishop move allows white to insist on the weak exchange of bishop for knight if Black plays 4 ... Pxe5 5 Qxd8 Kxd8 6 Nxe5 wins a pawn for white.
Mmmm Scholar's Mate. Or just rapid piece deployment
Keep pressure on f7 and add new pressure on b7

Sweet move if I do say so myself. 8 ... Qxg5 loses after 9 Bxf7  as follows:
If 9. ... Ke7 then 10. Qe6  Kd8 11. Qe8  
If 9. ... Kd7 then 10. Qd5  Nd7 11. Qxa8  Ke7 12. Qe8  Kd6 13. Qe6  Kc5 14. Qd5  Kb4 15. a3  Ka4 16 Nc3  . Not 12. ... Kf6 for then 13. Qe6  . If 10. ...Bd6 11 Qxa8 Qc1 ? 12. Ke2 Qxa1?? 13. Qxb8  Ke7 14. Qe8  Kf6 15. Qe6  Kg5 16. Qf5  K moves 17. Qh5  .
If 9. ... Kd7 then 10. Qd5  Bd6 11. Qxa8 Ke7! saves black's life but now 12. Qxb8 threatens the previous checkmates so 12. ... Kxf7 13. 0-0 and white is ahead in material and threatens to munch on black's pawns.
Need more pieces especially my rook on a1

Expecting Rc8 to save the pawn. Then white brings out his rook with 12. Rd1 followed by 13. Bxf6 and 14. Qxd7  . No none of that is forced but at this point white is just mounting attacks and bottling black up on the defence while I deploy more pieces.
Black overlooked mate in two.

Hi everyone.  I know this is against a newcomer to the game but this game is a perfect demonstration of the value of development.  I am not an advocate of memorizing hundreds of lines but everyone should learn the funamentals of opening theory.
New players should understand that while you're bringing the big guns out I'll be harrassing her all over the board while I bring out the rest of my pieces.
Gathering more space
preparing 5....Bg4 6.Qg3 e4
sidestepping the trap
I still want to control this very important diagonal.  Notice how I have developed 3 minor pieces and completely control the center while white has made 4 pawn moves and now 2 with his Q
When ahead in development and the oppsing K is uncastled open it up!!
This move loses material at best
threatening 9...Qd1# & 9...Bxa1

This annotation was not meant to brag about a checkmate.  Obviously my opponent is new to the game and still learning the ropes.  This was more of a shining example to other newcomers as to the importance of King safety and development.
A recent memorable game against a favorite opponent. Bunny obviously heavily favored to win looking at rating (although we are 2-2 lifetime going into this game).

My first mistake... As white I love playing the opening 1. d4 d5 2. e4 c5 (little-known fact: this is actually the official opening of my team the Pawn Stars)so my only guess is here I was laboring under two misconceptions: (1) I'm not playing white (2) opening was king's pawn not queen's pawn. Oops.
Somehow this is not what I was expecting to see...
...but undaunted I try to set up my fave opening anyway...
...this is looking worse all the time...
Second real mistake letting my knight get skewered against my queen.
Third mistake not even actually seeing it. Still thinking bishop at f5 is covered I push the d pawn.
D'ohh.
Here my priority is to release the skewer on the knight but this will shortly turn out to be not such a bad move for other reasons.
So much for my removing the skewer... now it's a genuine pin. Didn't have a lot of other options though. This is really not how I wanted the board to look at this point.
More punishment... black is not happy here.

It's a cliche but sometimes the best defense really is a good offense. This is one of those times. At this point the rook at h1 is doomed and there's not a whole lot white can do about it. Some responses are better than others though.
This was not one of the good ones. First real mistake for white.

Just throwing everything I have at white to keep the pressure on but in the meantime my king's side is in disarray (whatever's left of it is all over the map) meanwhile white is still in a pretty good defensive position and slightly better development.
White really has to get back on offense to turn this around...

My king is totally out there exposed and her queen is RIGHT THERE... it's like something out of a horror movie. One of the good ones. But I see a possible quick win with a tempting rook-for-knight trade (17. Rxd2 18. Rxd2 Qxg1  19. Rd1 Bg5  20. Kb1 Qxd1#. But I could also live with 18. Kxd2 19. Bg5  20. anything Qxh7)
White doesn't seem to like either of those options and instead of taking the bait goes back on offence... so looks like I got a free knight but otherwise things look black for black...
Or do they? Not that I have a choice but I realize at this point if I leave the a8 rook open and white takes it white loses...
O.o... shouldn't have done that white...
...but here have my other rook too... (white has no choice but to take it)
The rest is inevitable (probably a few different ways to get to mate from here)

Hi everyone!  Here is another game where I have had oodles of luck!  In this game my opponent has me well under the cosh until he blundered the exchange.  At the time of this blunder my rating was 1698 and his was in the 1770's.  I only needed a draw to get my rating to 1700 so I offered him one and he declined - this turned out to be yet another stroke of luck as I was able to stave off his attack and in the endgame the extra material proved decisive and so instead of 2 points I gain 8.8 points putting my rating back into the 1740s!  The action unfolds with a Queen's Pawn Opening.
3. ...... e6 - symmetry.
6. .......... Bd6 - over the last few moves I have countered in the centre and am ready to castle.  So how do I get into big big bother?  Well if your name is jstevens1 that is sooo easy!
9. ........ Qc7 - so far so good.

10. ......... Bb6?! - here is where I start to go wrong as this bishop retreat allows a pawn thrust to e5.  Would a pawn exchange on e4 have been preferable here?  If so there would have been the possibility of Glenda and Frere Lenoir lining up on the b8-h2 diagonal putting pressure on the h 2 square and leaving the possibility of a knight move to g4 to add still more pressure.  But this doesn't happen and a series of exchanges will leave me in Old Matey's shadow on the h file.

15. ......... Qf5 - Glenda answer's Henry's desperate cries for help.  The Wicked Witch of the West is threatening mate on h7.  Glenda could be driven off this square at any time though so quick action is needed.  We are still in the Gameknot 1900  database btw and the line is favourable to white.  However there is a game involving a guy called Bramster who played his bishop to d8 attacking the g5 knight and the game ended in a draw so I decided to go down that route.

17. Nh4 - taking me out of the database once and for all.  This move is very strong as it attacks Glenda.  Glenda moves to c2 staying on that vital diagonal.  Thankfully it will take a couple of moves before Glenda must move again and I will have time to exchange Frere Lenoir for that knight on g5.

19. .......... Qh7 - Glenda moves to h7 to drive off the Wicked Witch of the West.  White eschews the queen swap and puts a lot of pressure on my position.  My knight makes his way to the kingside to assist Henry and Glenda.

22. .......... Qxg6 - the remaining pair of knights are swapped off.  I am dreading an incursion of the Wicked Witch of the West to c7 but this does not happen.  She moves back to the h file instead and now I have a rook lift from white onto f3 preparing to swing onto h3 to worry about.  But as you will see Frere Leblanc will take care of all that!
24. ......... b6 - screens out white's dsb and releases my queen rook for action as he will not be tied down to the defense of my a pawn.
27. Rg3 - I now have a passer on the e file.  This passer will ultimately bag me the 8.8 rating swag!  Frere Leblanc backs up my weak d pawn on the next turn.

30. Rh3? - here white forgets about Frere Leblanc and puts his rook en prise.  I take the rook and here I offer my opponent a draw as explained in my introductory note.  He thinks he still has a strong attack so he declines.  However I manage to deal with it and he must surely regret this refusal.
33. ........ f6 - I think that this move finally swings the game in my favour.
36. ........ Qf5 - I now make him an offer he can't refuse - a queen trade!
41. ........ Rce7 - yet another offer he can't refuse - a trade off of his remaining rook.  I am slowly squeezing out every ounce of counterplay he has.

44. ....... Rf3 - keeping the enemy king tied down.  But how should I kill him off here?  I know Henry.  I have carefully calculated that he has enough time to get to g4 to protect my f3 rook and force white to give up his dsb.  Otherwise he will have Glenda to contend with!
47. ....... Ke6 - it's just two jumps to the right then two steps to the left!  But Henry has not come to do the Timewarp!
49. ......... Kg4 - after white potters aimlessly around with his dsb Henry reaches his destination.  He makes no attempt to even get his bishop into place to stop my e pawn from crowning!
51. ........ gxh6 - white gives up his h pawn - maybe it is to try and break my concentration - it does not wash with me however.  I just capture the pawn and await white's next move.

52. ........ e2 - white doesn't prevent my pawn's advance to e2.  Not only will Glenda appear on the board next move but it is mate in 3!  He waves the white flag.  This rounds off a nice weekend for me.  Au revoir!  Joanne

Opzione un po' strana da parte delle bianche ma forse volevano squilibrarmi. La presa dell'alfiere in un certo senso le aiuta ad occupare il centro ma non sono un problema per le nere.
In questo modo lascio il campo libero a c4 ma comunque ho gi� rinunciato ad arroccare di donna quindi mi posso occupare con calma di proteggermi sul fianco di donna.

Questo cavallo non pu� andare da nessuna parte penso che sarebbe stato meglio metterlo in e2... ma sono cose molto incerte.

AH! Questa me l'aspettavo. Ma perde una qualit�!

Catena solida di pedoni ma ho una qualit�. E via libera in g (anche se l� c'� il mio re!).
Ecco la posizione veramente interessante... contrattacco bianco sul centro re mio scoperto... mille viarianti.
Perché non Kh7?
Sto rinunciando ai due pedoni (e lasciandogli pedoni passati in abbondanza per compensare la qualit�) scommettendo di vincere con il mio attacco.

Se Tg6  si rifugiava in h1 e io non ero sicuro di fare in tempo. Forse s� ma...
questa non poteva essere sbagliata.
Se prendo il cavallo perdo un tempo preziosissimo.
Dh8  non portava a niente.

Preparing 2.d4 and bolstering the d4-square prior to moving there. This is a solid opening but a poor one development-wise as it stops the b1-knight from reaching its best square c3 and will waste a tempo if White decides to play c4 which is common in queen pawn openings.
A Nimzo-Indian setup except for White's pawn being on c3 instead of c4 - and White cannot play 3.Nc3 the main line of the NImzo-Indian.

Supporting the c4-square to prepare for 5.c4. I see nothing wrong with 4.c4 a belated version of the Queen's Gambit. 4.b3 also prepares to fianchetto White's dark-squared bishop...into what? It is then blocked by White's own pawn chain.
White needs to open up the queenside unblock his fianchettoed bishop and gain more space with c4 soon.

White appears to have a Slav Merano-type position but is very cramped - he needs to open his position up with c4. White has clearly not been learning his opening theory - in all queen pawn openings playing c4 is important.
Both sides castle kingside and the position appears to have stagnated - with both positions rather closed I can see no immediate opportunities for livening the position up.
The first sacrifice. White is looking to open up the h-file and put his queen on h3 threatening checkmate on h7. Of course the Black knight on f6 has to disappear first...
I can't see why White's queen doesn't go directly to h3.
An error by Black. After 14.c4 if Black moves the light-squared bishop then 15.c5 wins Black's trapped dark-squared bishop.
As we can see...
White can bide his time. Black's bishop isn't going anywhere...
With no coaxing needed Black's knight relinquishes its defence of h7. With White's light-squared bishop gone perhaps he sees no more threat...
Opening up Black's kingside even more. I think f6 would have been better preventing White's knight from approaching Black's kingside.
The second sacrifice. To completely shut off Black's e4-knight from the action and leave Black's pawn on g5 unprotected allowing a much more powerful checkmating threat
Turns a checkmate in two (Qh7  kf8 Qh8#) into a checkmate in one.
And when the smoke or dust (I can't remember which) has cleared Black has been checkmated. His extra rook as he has just realised no longer matters.
I think this is premature and that White should have transposed his second and third moves.  Had he played 2 Nf3 I would have played 2...d6 when 3 Bc4 would be a decent move.
Black seems to have already equalized.
With the Bishop on e7 Re1 could be awkward.
?? First blunder White would be OK after 15 Red1
18... Nde5 may be better.
28... Rf6 ck might be better
if 31 Kxg2? then ...Nf4 ck

?? This blunder is largely a bookkeeping error.   I  didn't have an internet connection at home and had been sending and receiving my moves from computers at the public library.  I had been analyzing 31 Rad1 instead of Rdd1.  When I went to the library to send my moves I failed to notice that the positon was not the one I had been analyzing.
While not at all happy about my blunder I did find the endgame interesting.
I would have played 37 Re8.
Again I would have played 38 Re8.

Besides guarding the f-pawn the knight blocks the White rook from e8.  I had made my fortress and waited to see how White would try to breach it.  I think White has a win here but it's not easy to make progress.
Generally White should avoid exchanging pawns.  I thought maybe White was trying to open the h-file for his rook but he never made an attempt to transfer his rook to the h-file.
It looks like White might make progress by playing d5 and answering ...Kd6 with Re6 ck.
Again White could try the 44 d5 Kd6 45 Re6 ck idea.
This doesn't seem like a very good place for a rook which is a long range piece and doesn't want to get in a knife fight.
I think the position may be drawn after this.  After the exchange on a5 any attempt by the rook to penetrate Black's position may result in all his pawns disappearing.
I felt very comfortable now and felt I could hold the draw with some chances at winning.
?? clearly a blunder.  The White rook steps into an open cage.
And the door to cage snaps shut.
Here black wasn't paying attention and white pulled off a tactic that messed up his position.
Now white has both center pawns and black only has one on the side.
Whoops.  Black should have paid closer attention.
At this point black thought "Well I'm a pawn down but at least I do have one advantage: I have a rook on the open column."  Then white proceeds to liquidate half the material in trades.
At this point black very nearly resigned.  It's so depressing to play a knight against a knight and a bishop.  Then he noticed a fancy fork against white's bishop and king to win a pawn.
Of course if white doesn't move the bishop black can fork it on the next move (N-e1).

Well ok.  So white managed to get his pawn back. BUT! NOW there are two beautiful isolated pawns on the edge of the board. In the worst case white can probably sacrifice a knight or a bishop and get both of them but who knows maybe black can work it into some other kind of advantage.
And the pawn is off.

Wow this is going really well (for black).  By chasing white's pieces around black was able to get his king to the other side of the board before white did.  White may still be able to trade a piece for both pawns if he tries hard.
Incidentally black could have defended the pawn on g7 but it seemed more valuable to get the king to c2 (and keep white's king out) than to save the pawn on g7.

Check is not always the best thing.  Black's king is actually better positioned now  so if white DOES manage to sneak his king in and get both pawns black can quickly get his king to the other side of the board and start capturing pawns.  Playing back and forth between the left and right is an important part of the endgame.
This time black is willing to take a move to save the pawn.
Now it is getting more desperate for white.  He may not be able to trade the knight for both pawns he may have to trade it for a single pawn.

At this point black (who was me) counted it would take him 4 (unanswered) moves to get a queen and if he tried for a queen by P-e4 e5 e6......it would take 5 (unanswered) moves.  Otherwise black would have been forced to move my king back to d5 to protect against the white pawn getting a queen.  It's an advantage to have your pawns closer to the other side of the board!!(unless the other king is close enough to capture them)
Black ignores the offer of the pawn.  There will be plenty of time to get all the pawns when black has a queen.
One final attempt at a tactic if P-b1 then Nxa3 forking the king and (new) queen.
And resignation.

Hi everyone just for once it is me that gets those pawns rolling!  This game against my buddy Bob Jacobs a player less than 100 points south of my rating is very even until well into the late middlegame when a pile up on the c file of my heavies leads to me winning a pawn due to a pin on his dark square bishop.  After that I still end up with work to do.  One big dilemma that I was faced with was "Should Glenda abandon the c file to the Wicked Witch of the West and if so where should she go?"  Thankfully that dilemma was somehow sorted with Glenda able to go back to that file.  A queen swap followed and I had a strong wall of passers.  It seemed plain sailing but I ask when is a jstevens1 victory plain sailing?  Not often.  In the end a knight move enabled me to put the advanced queenside pawns just where I wanted them.  Even him giving up his dsb would not have prevented a joyous reunion between Glenda and Henry so he waved the white flag.

He kicks off with the Caro-Kann Defense and I respond with the exchange variation hoping for open play.
4. ........ a6 - to prepare a b5 thrust.
6. Bf4 - Frere Lenoir develops onto what he hopes will be a productive diagonal for him.

9. 0-0 - fairly routine development up to here.  My queen knight has a dual function to give additional back up to my f3 knight and to contest the enemy knight's control of e4.  Henry is now tucked up in bed.

12. ......... bxc6 - a few exchanges have cleared the position a bit.  I didn't think that my e5 knight would be able to remain on that square for that much longer so I decided to trade it in.  At least the knight exchange leaves Bob with a queenside isolani which will weigh against him later on.
13. Be5 - Frere Lenoir takes the horse's place though.
15. Nf3 - opens up the possibility of putting another knight on that e5 square but the priority is to bolster that d4 pawn.

18. Nf3 - after a plethora of exchanges my knight drops back to f3 to cover the d4 pawn.  Black may have a slight edge here.  He now advances to a5 and this becomes an unfortunate choice of square for that poor little black pawn.

22. Qd2 - Oh dear now my d4 pawn is an isolani.  Thankfully this does not present too much of a problem but there is going to be some shuffling around of my heavies.  In the middlegame I am often faced with "Where do I go from here?"  Well that c file just needs to have a white rook on it before black gets the chance to bag it first.  Glenda supports the c1-c3 squares as well as the d4 pawn so that makes it ideal for a doubling even trippling on that file.  Note that if the a8 rook moves off the a file the black pawn on a5 is up for grabs.
25. g3 - as black does not have a light squared bishop then I create luft by pushing up my g pawn and carry on with my c-plan.
27. ....... Qb7 - the Wicked Witch is driven back.  Now comes the tripling.
29. Qc1 - Voila!
30. .......... f5?  I think black should have given that a pawn a little more back up.  Note that the dark squared bishop is PINNED!
32. ........ Rc7?! - Maybe Bc7 might have been better my rook may well have been short of squares.  Now the other pair of rooks are exchanged and we are approaching the endgame.
35. a4 - passed pawns must be pushed if safe to do so.
36. Qd3 - here I decide to cede the c file temporarily.  Thank heaven Henry has the g2 square to escape to should the Wicked Witch land a check on c1.

38. Qc5 - Glenda is allowed to move onto the c file and now a queen trade is forced.  Although it allowes black a d pawn passer I now have 3 queenside passers.  The knight on f3 now becomes a knight in shining armour to me.

41. ........ Bc7 - If Bxb4?? then Bob's dsb is decoyed away from the a5-d8 diagonal which will allow Glenda to reappear with disastrous results for Bob.  My pawns now start their roll down the queenside.
42. Nd4 - d-d-d-l-d-d!! In gallops the knight.  He is heading for b3 to stop the enemy king invading on c5 should the pawn chain remain on a4 b5 and c6.

45. Kf1 - in the endgame it is vital for the king to be centralised even more so here.  Black starts a pawn roll of his own and both Henry and his steed must work together to contain them as well as protect that vital pawn wall on the queenside.
47. .......... Bb8 - that bishop will be cut off soon.

52. Nd4!! - This move proves decisive.  Henry's steed threatens to pick off the f pawn with check.  But he also provides two other vital roles.  Firstly he defends my c pawn.  Secondly he prepares b6 which will entomb that dark squared bishop.  Even if the black king were to move then at least Henry would not have to dodge a check from the dsb before I had a chance to entomb him.  He decides to back up the f pawn with his g pawn.  Now comes the coup de grace.

54. a7 - and with this move black waves the white flag as he will in two moves be down a whole queen and Glenda will clean up those black pawns with consumate ease before netting the black king.  An interesting endgame battle because in the final position just look at that impressive black pawn chain of Bob's!  He just got pipped at the post.  Hope you have had a good read.  Bye for now.   Joanne

This is from a tournament game. My first tournament in the advanced class. I decided to annotate this game for posterity as it took my rating over 1600 for the first time ever. There are a number of mistakes on both sides but in the end it was pretty close

D4 is my preferred opening as white. I suspect I may have to change that if my rating continues to rise. Up to know it has served me well partly I suspect as some of my opponents don't know it as well as other openings
Tries to pressure me into either a3 or Bd2

I ignore the pressure and continue to develop  as I normally do. In the past Bxc3bxc3 has often proved to my advantage despite the weaker pawn structure as the doubled pawns have given me more influence over the centre
Looking at h7 but also allows me to prevent my pawns being doubled if he takes my knight. I normally move e3 too which defends both my c and d pawns
Trying to seize the initiative and attacking my undefended c pawn

Attack is the best form of defence they say though I am still not sure if c5 would have been better here. I was reluctant to take his d pawn as it would give a half open e file to my still uncastled king
I'm not sure this was wise as black loses his best developed peice though it does prevent a loss of tempo
A strong outpost for the knight which is difficult to shift
Loses a tempo however this seems the best place for my queen putting it on d3 will restrict my lsb similarly Qb3 will block my b pawn
Blocks in the lsb completely and slightly restricts the queen. Is this a sign of a forthcoming pawn storm on the queens side?
Allows me to finally move e3 and may restrict his a rook a little if the pawn storm materialises
This seems a very passive move to me though it gives the queen a little more room to move I think I would have been tempted by c5
I'm not clear why he did this presumably an attempt to get me to move my king with something like 11: Nd2 Nxd2  12: Qxd2 Qxd2  13:Kxd2
This is exactly why Qc2 was probably the best move at move 8
Pretty much the only option so black has lost tempo and still can't develop his lsb
As well as pressuring his knight I can now (finally) castle
Black seems a little cramped now. it's still going to take him a couple of moves to complete his development

That completes my development and links my rooks. I have a nice line of pawns on bc and d ready to push forward a reasonable diagonal for my dsb - h2-b1 and my queen and lsb are aiming straight at h7. My knight has a number of options such as e5 and g5. at e5 it would be difficult to move and would cramp black further though it would block my dsb's diagonal
The predicted pawn storm isn't forthcoming so I threaten one of my own
Eyeing up my queen which means I need to be careful in any pawn exchanges
Pressuring the e knight One option here is Bxe4 dxe4 Qxe4 Nxe4 Bxd8 R(either) xd8 which gains a pawn and I think gives white a slight lead

This way is similar but preserves more attacking power.

Is it a mistake to swap a reasonably well placed dsb for a knight here? I was looking to break up the linked knight hence weakening blacks defence. As my dsb wasn't that active in threatening his king directly this seemed a reasonable exchange to me
Almost forced if he took with his queen then I could push my pawns forward on the queens side and he would take at least a move to get his queen back to defend
If in doubt move a piece to a better square though I think now that c1 would probably have been better
Prevents Ng5 though Ne5 is still tempting
This is probably my first ever serious (conscious) attempt at a pawn storm. Although I wasn't fully clear that it would work as I hoped I was expecting the a file to open for my rook
Is this a mistake? Would Bxb5 be better? I now have a very nice open file for my a rook as I hoped
Doubled pawns aren't always weak in this case he has enough support
I think this is a mistake I think Rdc1 is better (or would have been on move 17)
I now have a passed pawn although the way for it to achieve its ambition isn't clear it poses a threat to black
This is a complete blunder I was concentrating too much on the black lsb
At this point I was considering resigning however I decided to continue a short while to see how the game looked
Stops the black b pawn pushing too far forward. It can easily be defended where it is
Relieves the pressure on my c pawn
Considering c6 and the possibilities that opens.
where is my knight when I need it!
Another complete blunder by black even's up the game again in terms of material. I am in with a chance once again.
Blocks the b1h7 diagonal for my lsb which could have caused some problems for black
Concedes the b pawn
but the price is too high for me I want to keep my passed pawn. It;s just a pity I didn't put this rook there on move 17
Now I can try to free the path for my c pawn
removes the last defender from my c pawn
I still can't put enough defence on my b pawn so I have to look for something else
Looking at e8
I would say this is a big mistake. Surely Qxc5 is better.
regains the material
This is a fatal mistake by black

I chose to annotate this game because I think it is a good example of how a few passive moves by a player can lead to a positional advantage for his opponent.
I always choose the symmetrical variation of the English as I know it well and the Botvinnik setup is not as effective.

As usual my annotations are for players who have more than a basic understanding of the game. If you dont understand the basic opening moves that I leave unannotated there are several good books out there.

If White were to continue to maintain flexibility with his king's knight by playing 3.g3 then I would continue the symmetrical motif.  Here I decide to play a "Botvinnik" setup myself although it's technically called the Wedberg variation when black adopts it after Swedish GM Tomas Wedberg.
4. e3 and 4. d3 are all main lines also.
The plan is to castle and play ...f5 or ...d5 at some point depending on which setup White adopts.
Play typically continues with 7. d3 although we do transpose back to the main variation.  Here White wants to play a3 followed by b4 to break apart the bind on the d4 square.
Sensibly preventing b4.
Not the most critical variation.  Other moves are Bg5 and Ne1.

This is what we in the chess world call 'weak sauce'.  There are four alternatives that are critical in the position the most interesting in my opinion is 11. Qa4 Be6; 12. Ng5 Bd7; 13. Nge4 Nd4; 14. Qd1 Bc6; 15. b4.
Preparing to play ...Be6 without having to worry about Ng5.

Here I had anticipated 12. e4 when Black has the ...f5 break and the initiative.  I would say it's probably dynamically equal or very slightly better for Black.  At any rate Black has won the opening battle and achieved easy equality.
13.  e3 is interesting here although black has no problems after 13...Bf5.
I considered 13...Bg4 but decided that I was going to play ...f5 and wanted to keep the Bishop behind the pawns rather than swap it for the knight of f3.

I am kind of confused at this move maybe White was thinking he was going to play e3 and d4.  Its possible to reroute the dark-squared bishop to b2 via c1 after b3 also.  White's play is slow and I decide to begin a kingside attack.
Not possible is ...d5 when 15. cd Nxd5; 16. Nxd5 Bxd5; 17. Qxc5 just drops a pawn for no compensation.
Better is 15. e3.
Now 16. e3 gives Black a huge initiative after 16...fg; 17. fg Bg4; 18. Rf1 e4!?; 19. de Ne5.

The center is now closed and the White rooks are both made poor.  White's position lacks any dynamic aspect and he will have to sit while I crank up the pressure on the position.  Admitting the positional mistakes with 16. Rf1 seems to be better.  White can at least hold for the time being.
finishing development and linking the rooks.  I also had the idea of bringing a rook to the d-file as to relieve my queen of the defense of the d-pawn.
Get's out of the way of the rooks but White has no pawn breaks in the position.  In this type of position if you don't have any breaks you dont have any play!
With the situation in the center and the Queen's wing under control I start to use my intiative on the kingside.
Gets out of the way of the ...g4 push and prepares to play f3 to mitigate the Black pawn storm.
Pressing on!
f3 or gf is better.  This allows Black to completely seal the White position.
Bf1 is to be preferred although it really doesnt matter at this point.
The plan now is to break through on the h-file.
Routing the knight to e3 will give it some much needed activity.  White's pieces are basically dying.

The idea behind 16th move comes to fruition.  The queen will go to ...f7 and after ...Nxh5 the h-file invasion will be decisive.

I annotated my other game against mrcollio in this mini-tournament a little while ago. I was playing extra carefully in this the return match because I knew he would be after revenge!
I play the French Defence my favourite response to 1.e4.

If my opponent wanted to get me "out of the book" he has certainly managed it! This is the Reti/Spielmann Variation very rare in comparison the the main line 2.d4 and I had never seen it before in my life. Not a good start.
I simply continued with the core idea of the French Defence pretending it was the main line. This is the most usual response to the Reti/Spielmann Variation as well.
The game broadens into a more usual French formation - though still a far cry from main line French Defence.

Black's position is unfortunately very cramped with both bishops completely blocked in. In particular Black's light'squared bishop is stuck behind Black's c- and e- pawns as well as his d2-knight - at least Black's dark-squared bishop has an easy exit after Ng6. However I was hoping to target the pawn on e5 which was not currently protected by any other pawns: if this pawn falls Black can expand his cramped postion.

White throws a spanner in the works shoring up his e-pawn with another pawn. I could almost see my position recoiling before my eyes from the constricting advance of the d-pawn.
So I unveil the time-honoured way of undermining the d-pawn in the main line French Defence.
And White allows Black to undermine his pawn formation without a struggle leaving the e5-pawn weak again! Excellent! I could see a glimmer of daylight.
Now the knight is pinned. Black can play 11...Nd7 to place incredible pressure on the e5-pawn...
...or put more pressure on the pinned knight on d2 - a strategy with a lower probability of success but one which will reap greater rewards if it does succeed - namely the d2-knight.
Black is trying to stretch White's defences and overwork his pieces. Notice that attention has completely shifted from the e5-pawn to the d2-knight!

Complicating the position adding more attack lines...all part of the effort to over-stretch White's defences. As White's king is defending the d2-knight the king is as bound to the knight as the knight is bound to the king! And if the king is stuck in the centre Black has an advantage.
I judged that it was time to begin exchanging on d2.
Black starts attacking White's queenside pawns in an attempt to gain material.
This looks like a mistake by White: it appears to lose him a pawn.
And now White is behind by a pawn.
It appears to me that White's exposed kingside can offer White's king no more protection than the centre can: at best this was a waste of a move.
That's the way I like my opponent's rooks to be: tied down to their pawns.
Suddenly attention shifts. Now the pressure starts piling up against - you've guessed it - the e5-pawn. The e5-pawn is under multiple attacks for the second time in the game.
An aggressive pawn move: perhaps White is going in for an attack on Black's kingside.

Hi everyone I have decided to annotate a couple of very lucky wins.  After the disappointing result of the Beafyness tourney two players put a smile on my face by waving the white flag.  But as you will see from these two games the chessic illness I suffer from passivitis is still with me.  But I got away with it and as a result you could certainly call me a lucky so and so!  This game started out as a Guicco Piano.
3. ........ Bc5 - these moves characterise the centre-contesting Guicco Piano.
5. Nc3 - becomes more like a 4 kts game here.
6. ....... a6 - preparing a b5 possibility.  I do get in this pawn break but it leaves my c6 pawn backward and weak.
7. ......... 0-0 - dealing with the minor piece pile up on my weak f7 pawn.  Here we leave the database behind.
10. cxb3 - this exchange of N for B breaks the pin on my f pawn and doubles up white's queenside pawns.
12. Qe2 - sensible development from my 1300  opponent.
14. ......... h6 - after another exchange of minor pieces I have had enough of that enemy knight camped out on g5 back he jolly well goes!

17. ......... Qc7 - white has an excellent position and has made the thematic break d4.  Take note Joanne Stevens.  Glenda does her usual - adds defensive back up to d and e pawns x ray style along the diagonal.

22. Rfd1! - here it looks as though white can open some lines here to his advantage.  I did analyse that I would be a pawn down in a wretched position.  I was seriously considering waving the white flag.  Had it been an Expert or dmaestro I probably would have but wait my opponent has a 1300  rating.  I will see what he does on his next move before I make any decisions.  I play Be6 and say my prayers.
23. b4 - and my prayers get answered.  This is the start of some irrelevant moves by my opponent which lets me off the hook!
24. ........... hxg5 - I end up with a doubleton on the kingside but I get rid of one of white's steeds and do not  have to worry about my own steed being dim on the rim!

25. ....... g6 - ah - I forgot to mention that with the exchange of knights the h file is open.  Henry is rather draughty here but behold - my second rank is empty but for one piece - Glenda!  If she senses danger to her other half she will be over there believe you me but first I have the seed of an idea of attacking the enemy king down the h file and it germinates over the next few moves and it will be me with the extra booty!
29. Qf3 - first my opponent gives away a pawn.
30. ...... Rh8 - here I am planning to put Glenda on c8 piling up on the pinned h3 pawn.  White moves his rook to f1 on move 31 and his knight to g1 on move 32 to guard this beleagured h3 pawn.

32. Ng1 - however because of the pin on the h file the Wicked Witch of the West is skewered to her castle by Frere Leblanc on my next turn and me already a pawn up will now be the exchange for a pawn up!
35. ......... Qe7 - now it is my turn to b****r about.  I think I should have got in my g5 move here instead of next move.  To lose one tempo can be costly.  Thankfully not here.

37. .......... g4 - a pleasant surprise awaits me in that he waves the white flag.  In his resignation note he said that he felt that I was subjecting him to slow strangulation.  Me jstevens1 doing that to an opponent?  Well maybe I am starting to learn some lessons from my higher rated opponents and am finally putting them into practice!  Joanne
Hi everyone!  As I said at the end of my last annotation.  Now for the good news!  This game starts off as a Scotch Opening.

3. d4 - this move characterises the Scotch Opening - it challenges the centre and interesting play results.  Just for the benefit of newcomers to the annotations gallery my first ever game with Coach Ion which I annotated as Battle of the Wings started off as a Scotch.  White deviates to a Goring Gambit on his next move.

4. ........ dxc3 - I accept this gambit with some trepidation as when I looked in the database the first thing I saw was the Sea Cadet Mate.  That mate is similar to Legal's Mate.  However playing through that game I made myself a mental aide memoir.  Do not play Bg4!
7. ......... Qd7 - to defend the weak f7 pawn.
9. ........ c6 - to screen out that lsb's attack on Glenda.
12. Nxc3 - after an exchange of white's lsb for my knight white finally collects my c3 pawn.  I now gain a vital developmental tempo for Frere Lenoir with Bc5

14. Nxb5 - I decided to let the b pawn go in order to tuck Henry away on the kingside and to bring another defender to the weak pawn on f7 which is pinned against Henry.  Somehow I must drive the Wicked Witch of the West off the a2-g8 diagonal.

14. ........ Qc6 - opens up Frere Leblanc's diagonal.  My next move h6 prepares the possibility of putting Fere Leblanc on e6 developing my bishop connecting my rooks and driving the Witch off that diagonal unpinning the f7 pawn by driving back the white knight.
16. ......... Re8 - backing up my e pawn.

17. ....... Qb6 - here I froze.  This was the first time that I had managed to maintain a clear pawn lead against an Expert.  There seemed to be no weaknesses but this just seemed too good to be true.  I let the emotional baggage from my past performances against the Expert colour my judgement here.  I offered Jim a draw.  I half expected a refusal.  If the refusal was to come with an exchange of queens I would recapture with Frere Lenoir otherwise Frere Leblanc would come to e6 and drive back the Witch followed by the move Ne7 to protect my e pawn and to prepare f6 to bolster it.  But he accepted the draw offer and I received 7.1 points for this high draw.  At the end of the game Ion assessed the position as Black has a clear advantage.  I suppose in one way I am in a win win situation here.  If the advantage is with white then it was a good draw offer.  If it was a bad draw offer then it is nice to end the game with the better of things against a player 300 points north of my rating.  In any case it ensured that although I came bottom of the league I did not leave Beafyness' tourney with nul point.  It was Un Demi Point.

Hi everyone just to say that I am annotating my final two remaining games in Beafyness' tournament.  These two are against a strong Expert called therealjimfriar.  Jim has recently beaten an international master so I was pleased to come away with half a point out of my two games with him.  I think I will give you the bad news first with this game which started off as a Ruy Lopez Exchange Variation.

5. ......... Bg4 - this is recommended as the strongest response to the standard book 5. 0-0.  It is trappy.  You try to drive black's lsb away with h3 but wait black plays h5.  You really have to be careful about when you take that bishop because you as white may cop Old Matey on the open h file after the Wicked Witch of the West comes to h4!
7. d3 - opens up Frere Lenoir's diagonal.
10. d4 - counters in the centre.  I just wonder if I should have taken on e5 at an opportune moment.

14. ........ Rxh4 - this plethora of exchanges gives some relief to white down the h file but there could still be a doubling of the rooks to contend with.  My next move Nf3 clears Fere Lenoir's diagonal and puts the question to the black rook.
16. Bf3 - develops my last piece - in the world database it does have a good percentage rating in favour of white.
17. g3 - still following the sequence in the database and creating g2 for Henry to bolster a rook challenge on the h file but I wonder whether I should have exchanged on e5 here.
20. ......... c5 - and here Jim takes me out of the database and starts the pawns rolling.  In order to avoid dropping a pawn here I must retreat Frere Lenoir to c3.

26. Bd2 - Jim has achieved a lot in his last few moves.  He now gets the pawn majority on the queenside.  I move the rook to a1 but would Rh7 have been a better try here hitting at the g7 pawn and tying down one of black's pieces to it and then using one of my minor pieces to deal with the queenside pawn roll.
32. Ne1 - I eschew exchanges on e5 to try and get my knight to take over defensive duties of a1 - Jim does not give me the chance to do this however.
32. ........ Nc6 - gains a tempo by attacking Frere Lenoir who retreats to e3.
34. ......... bxa3 - Jim's mission is accomplished.  One deadly passer on the a file.
36. Bb2 - to try and prevent the enemy dsb from controlling that a1-h8 diagonal.  Jim forces a trade of bishops on his next move.
37. ........ Kxe5 - recaptures with the king - this king is making his way down to b2.

38. .......... Kd4.  There is no way I can stop Jim's king from getting to b2.  Henry is too far away to help and neither he nor his steed can stop Jim's plan so I wave the white flag.  On to my next annotation - now for the good news ..................

I don't often meet Alekhine's Defence.  The idea of the opening is for Black to encourage White to overreach himself and then to strike back exploiting the holes in White's defences.  So in planning to meet it White either has to guard against over-exuberance or make sure that his attack wins quickly - not an option against a decent player of the Black pieces.
? Exposing Black's Queen too early in the game.  This contradicts opening principles generally and in the Alekhine particularly.  4...exd6 or 4....cxd6 were much safer.
? a second Queen move before Black has developed his other pieces.  However White must be careful not to try to "punish" his opponent too soon or he will also fail to develop quickly.

?  An unusual choice by me.  I usually prefer to keep my Bs and swap off Ns.  It removes the defender of e7 but I don't think it is justified for tactical or strategic reasons - only material.

When I was younger I always played knight to c6 the most commonly made 2nd move but after a while I got to thinking... When I play white I play the exact same opening so why should I do what I would want me to do if I was playing me?
So I looked for something different about 8 months into my GK life and I found this. Things begin to happen much faster with this opening and some players even make an early blunder thus allowing me an easy advantage.
Not the most common white response but I don't mind it at all. I like to escape the monotony of boring four knights openings. :)
This move was just trying something new. I saw it in the database and liked it so I figured: why not? It looked fun. So I played it.
Seems free right?
Well okay not FREE per se. Bishop's only safe retreat gets the bishop and knight forked.
A fine move the pieces were going to be exchanged anyways white just did it his way.

An inevitable loss... the castling king. I believe that this is why I ended up with a losing position coming into the end game. It's now going to take me 3 moves to castle at the very minimum. White even has ways of stopping that castle from ever taking place.

All white wants to do right now is develop before black has a chance- white's advantage is that he can spend 2 extra moves developing while blacks trying to castle. I don't know if I agree with this move however as black then gets a bishop exchange AND moves his king to e7 leaving only 2 moves left in his castle and now white no longer has moves to stop the castle. White has just effectively shortened his 2 move lead to a one move lead.

I think I might have just pulled back to f4 as white even after the wasted check. I don't understand why white wants to trade bishops as if black ever gets the initiative back his white bishop can be a lot more powerful than white's knight.
Re8 or Rd8 allow me to get my king into a castled position as well as either attacking a pawn or taking a file.
Again white is developing. It's obvious he would like to queen side castle immediately laying claim to the d file but there is nothing black can do to stop that.
Bishop protects pawn only logical move I found.
White completes his queen side castle still a move up on black.

At this point I'm willing to exchange for the open d file because my e pawn and bishop may be able to team up with my rook to make a better attack than his knight can ever hope to achieve.
Better for black is Ke6 attacking the week pawn and leaving the king in the middle of the board- if the rooks get traded black is going to want to be in the center not back on f8.
So white now gains a pawn. Kd7 doesn't work because of the double check from Nb6. All right well this isn't a devastating set back is it? We'll soon see for sure.

Okay the good news is that black has finally completed his castle. The bad news is that it is now much harder for black to get his king into the battle against the e5 pawn which he should have done earlier.
White has guaranteed a winning endgame position here.

It seems to me this was a stupid mistake on my part. I did not have to give up the open file and I didn't have to trade rooks right now as more trading will only bring the end game that much quicker and I'm already down a pawn.
Obvious move claiming the open file.

The only rational move this move also has a look on the c2 square if ...e3 fxe3 Rxc2  and then white's pawns are reduced to cannon fodder. However this is no more than a dream as whites Nd5 immediately quashes all hopes for that.
Now if ...e3 then Nxe3 thus protecting the c2 square as well as attacking blacks winning bishop.
At this point I'm desperate to get the pawn back... the end is coming closer and closer by the second and I'm frantically trying what I can.
Attacks the bishop but allows black to gain the pawn back. I make the mistake of assuming I have to get the pawn now and lose my strong bishop because of it.
Well at least we have an even score and the position could be worse for black.
So now black is attacking white's fgh pawns with the hopes and dreams of one day pushing that e pawn for the win. Hopes and dreams nothing more.
White forsakes his pawns for the exchange.
Even again.

A hasty mistake it seems.
The king moves in of course. If e2 then Ke1 blocks the queening and now black can't even look at the cba pawns without a lot more work.
black takes the pawn now better late than never.
Now as black I want to get my f-pawn into the attack. The rook moved over giving him a clear shot the problem is that it will take way too many moves to even get that pawn close enough.
White even has time to push his pawns setting up for a better position after the exchange.
Now white looks to fork on f5. Very easy to avoid really.
Or....you could just not avoid it? Can't honestly tell you what was going through my head... a very sharp needle or something I'd assume.
Losing the pawn here is devastating for black but it's not over yet. Let's see what the king can accomplish.
Okay so now I have to push or the pawn gets it.
Enjoying a light snack of pawn crunchables.
Pushing more pieces towards the queening ranks. Blacks going to have trouble now.

I chose to move my rook back to attack the pawns as c3 solidifies white's position too much for my likings.
Instead I'm going to see if my h pawn can promise any death and destruction after an exchange.
Okay so white finally chooses to win the pawn. Once the rooks are traded there will be no stopping the a b c pawns from marching to victory.

That powerful e pawn has finally taken his last breath. *funeral music plays in the distance* If not for that stupid f pawn dropping the e pawn may have one day grown up to be the queen but she was stabbed in the back by one of her closes friends.
Then I trade roo---- wait what? No! I can't trade rooks! Not yet! I must keep trying!
But of course! Secures white's little pawn party which of course I wasn't invited to.
Okay so now that I got rid of the pesky f pawn there will be nobody to stop the g pawn from achieving her goal of becoming a queen right? Well... you'll have to wait and see!
White's trying to limit blacks squares and succeeding give the cba pawns even more power.
White doesn't want black moving to h3 it seems.
Perhaps maybe I can still get a draw by getting my rook to do enough damage to the cba crew before white picks of my last few men?
The king wants to join the battle...
White's king claims the corner making it harder for me to run my g and h pawns up after any exchange of rooks.

Okay so white's now just taking his time. If black moves c4 and tries to exchange rooks the a pawn becomes a queen faster than you can say taco sauce!
But it's not over yet!

And now I see it. Remember the e pawn earlier betrayed by her dearest friend f who was secretly working with the white side and ruined her chances of ever becoming a queen? Well do you also remember then that the g pawn who can no longer be betrayed by the evil f pawn also one day wants to become a queen?
Well it just so happens that there's a third piece that wants to one day be promoted. The h pawn. He however hopes to one day be a rook as he's really not into cross-dressing. And he's willing to do anything he has to do it. Luckily his high school buddy the rook is willing to help!
Step one: force the white king out of the corner unless white instead chooses to have a draw. Yeah right.
Back and forth we go where we're headed nobody knows! Okay so basically anywhere not on the e file really.
Now that black has gotten the king out of the corner phase two of the plan begins: shove your buddy in front of the guard and make a run for it.
It's the guards duty to kill trespassers so that's what he does of course.
Run pawn run! RUN!!!
White see's what's coming and he decides to take this free move to get his pawns one space closer to a queen of his one.
I want to be in front of the pawns once any trading goes down.
Okay so the rook finally decides to attack the h pawn.
Aaaaand now he's safe again.
But where on Earth will my king go? Oh no!
White decides to poke the rook though I can't for the life of me tell you what he hopes to get out of it.
So at this point I finally open my eyes and say "enough of this crap!"
White has to stay on h to avoid getting mated.

And now remember how that h pawn would do anything to become a rook? Sacrifice his buddy? Endanger his old friend the rook? Well he wants to be a rook so bad even if only for a second that he's willing to die for it. And that's exactly what he does.
NOW the game gets interesting. black has gone from a slight hope to draw to a chance at winning.
Black's king however has a long ways to go to get in the battle.
This was a mistake. I eventually wanted to get the rook down here but not until later: I needed him to be able to get behind the c pawn later if I wanted a chance to win.
If that king doesn't get to b8 before his pawns push too much all is for naught.
And now we're fine. Rook jumps around a bit not allowing white to do anything at all and eventually white accepts a draw.
